included.summary:
Hello! Iâm a versatile qualitative UX researcher who is passionate about making experiences better for people. I love learning about humans - what makes them tick, how they work, and why they do the things they do. With a foundation in psychology and anthropology, I employ a variety of research methods to listen, understand, and evaluate in order to create actionable insights that improve products and processes for users. I work collaboratively and cross-functionally with international agile teams of interaction designers, visual designers, marketers, product managers, content strategists, and developers in order to translate insights into implementation. I serve as the âvoiceâ of the user, representing their goals and needs to product teams in order to create a truly user-centered product.

Methodologies:
* Interviews (remote and in-person)
* Surveys
* Usability studies 
* Cognitive walkthroughs
* Contextual inquiry/ethnographic research
* Card sorting
* Diary studies
* Competitive analysis
* A/B testing
* Randomized and controlled testing
* Heuristic analysis

Outside of work, you're likely to catch me with my nose in a book (usually fantasy!), hunting for the best BBQ in the Bay Area (just a little taste of home), playing board games with friends (having fun but probably not winning), or catching up on the most popular new show (recent fave: Westworld!)

included.description:
The Broke App is a money management application for college students that provides relevant, understandable, and actionable information to students so that they can build and maintain good financial habits. Unlike current budgeting apps that stop simply at tracking categories of spending, the Broke app puts spending in context for its users - when, where, and why money was spent. Similar to fitness apps, Broke helps promote "financial fitness" by gradually helping users develop and maintain good financial habits.

included.title: The Broke App

included.description: My task for this project was to design the user experience of an interaction that will be placed inside of the installation itself, once constructed. I visualized an interaction that would allow the user to "fly" through a digitally rendered crafts cluster, a small area where craftspeople live and work together. The research conducted by Jaaga discovered that only one living crafts cluster remains in the UNESCO World Heritage Site of Hampi, so this is an ideal focal point for users to discover the stories of the craftspeople and to learn what their process for craftsmaking might be.

included.name: Information Behavior Shift: How and Why Medical Students Use Facebook
included.description: The poster offers a unique opportunity to learn about the information behavior of a group of medical students using a social networking site (SNS) group over the period of almost three, full, consecutive, academic years without faculty supervision to facilitate their learning. Mixed methods approach to data collection and analysis allowed us to obtain a comprehensive overview of the SNS group usage and conclude that it played an important role in student learning. Patterns of the group utilization became the evidence of extending the classic principles of PBL in medical education into a digital learning environment, which, in its turn, results in gradual transformation of medical studentsâ information behavior. By shifting from more traditional forms of communication and information technology to using content available through social media, medical students incorporate SNS in their learning as an online environment that supplements their face-to-face interactions and facilitates acquisition and/or exchange of school-related information in easier, more efficient ways.
